Step 1: Set Up Google Secret Manager

To prevent security vulnerabilities, by placing hardcode database credentials in clear text inside code repositories or text configuration files. We are storing passwords inside Secret Manager isolating credentials behind strict IAM-controlled access blocks.
Detailed Actions:

1.	In Google Cloud Console and launch the Cloud Shell environment.

2.	Enable the central security service API by running the following deployment instruction:

Bash command 

gcloud services enable ://googleapis.com

3.	Instantiate a protected secret storage container to hold your source database connection assets:

Bash command

gcloud secrets create teradata-migration-password --replication-policy="automatic"

4.	Pipe your actual corporate Teradata production service-account password string directly into the secret container as a secure latest version entry:

Bash command

echo -n "YourTeradataSecurePassword123" | gcloud secrets versions add teradata-migration-password --data-file=-
